summary:
The Security Council,
Reaffirming previous resolutions on terrorism, 
Reaffirming the imperative to combat terrorism in all its forms, stressing States must ensure measures comply with international law, 
Condemning all acts of terrorism, 
Condemning also incitement of terrorist acts and repudiating attempts to justify or glorify terrorist acts,
Deeply concerned by incitement of terrorist acts motivated by extremism and intolerance, 
Recalling right to freedom of expression and right to seek asylum, 
Reaffirming acts, methods and practices of terrorism are contrary to UN purposes and principles, 
Deeply concerned by increasing victims of terrorism, 
Recognizing the essential role of the UN in combating terrorism, 
Stressing its call upon all States to become party to international counter-terrorism Conventions and Protocols, 
Re-emphasizing international efforts to enhance dialogue and broaden understanding among civilizations, 
Stressing the importance of the role of media, civil and religious society, business community and educational institutions, 
Recognizing the importance of States acting cooperatively to prevent terrorists exploiting technology, communications and resources.
1624 (2005)

The Security Council:

Recalling States' obligation to cooperate in the fight against terrorism,

1. Calls upon States to adopt measures to:
(a) Prohibit by law incitement to commit a terrorist act;
(b) Prevent such conduct;
(c) Deny safe haven to persons suspected of such conduct;

2. Calls upon States to cooperate to strengthen international border security, combat fraudulent travel documents, and enhance terrorist screening;

3. Calls upon States to enhance dialogue among civilizations, counter incitement of terrorist acts motivated by extremism and intolerance, and prevent subversion of educational, cultural, and religious institutions;

4. Stresses that measures taken must comply with international law, particularly human rights, refugee, and humanitarian law;

5. Calls upon States to report to the Counter-Terrorism Committee on implementation;

6. Directs the Counter-Terrorism Committee to:
(a) Include implementation efforts in its dialogue with States;
(b) Help build capacity through best practices and information exchange;
(c) Report back to the Council in twelve months;

7. Decides to remain seized of the matter.
